# Space Invaders clone - runs with Triton L7.2 monitor. #

# From a hex dump in Computing Today (March 1980; page 32). #
# Copyright (c) is claimed in the magazine (page 3) but the #
# copyright holder is not identified. #
# No license terms were given - the code is hereby presumed to be #
# clonable under the equivalent of a modern open source license. #

# The further changes listed below to make this work with Triton #
# L7.2 are hereby released into the public domain (PBW, January 2021). #

# Note that a later Computing Today (May 1980; page 9), contains #
# an erratum news item 'Begging your pardon' but just to say the #
# printed hex dump is for a Level 5.2 Triton. #

# There are some minor changes to make this work : #

# at 1600 changed 40 1C to 41 1C for the tape end; #
# at 18B6 changed CD BC 00 to CD 4A 01 (L7.2 monitor call); #
# at 1A20 changed CD E3 00 to CD D4 00 (L7.2 monitor call); #
# at 1C32 changed 00 to 20 (ASCII space) - seems to be spurious. #

# Monitor routines : (undocumented) L7.2 replacements as above #

# 00BC DLY    (3ms delay)    in L5.2  <-->  014A in L7.2 #
# 00E3 CLRSCN (clear screen) in L5.2  <-->  00D4 in L7.2 #

# Control keys are '[' (ASCII 0x5D) and ']' (ASCII 0x5B) for #
# left and right; and 'escape' (ASCII 0x1B), 'carriage-return' #
# (ASCII 0x0D) or 'up-arrow' (ASCII 0x7B) for fire. #

# These are hard-coded at 18E5 - 18FF. #

# Note that the code reads the keyboard port directly (port 0x00) #
# and tests for the presence of the strobe bit (bit 8) to discover #
# if a key is being pressed.  A further test (at 18E5-18FF) is made #
# to discover which key was pressed.  This test is for the above #
# ASCII code *with the strobe bit (bit 8) set*.  The control codes #
# can be changed by amending the tests in the block 18E5-18FF. #

# At the end of a game press 'G' to start a new game #

# The code seems to expect that memory top is at 0x2000. #
# This corresponds to the main-board RAM on a standard Triton. #
# If the RAM exceeds this, writing 0xFF into memory at 0x2000 #
# seems to work in fooling the code that this is the memory top. #

